# Accessibility Rules

These are hard constraints, not suggestions. The primary user has Parkinson's disease. Every UI decision is evaluated against their motor and cognitive profile first.

## Touch targets

Every interactive element — buttons, links, toggles — must have a minimum tap target of 48x48px. Use padding rather than fixed height so text scales correctly.

**Wrong:**

```html
<a href="/articles/42">Read more</a>
```

**Correct:**

```html
<a href="/articles/42" class="article-link">Read more</a>
```

```css
.article-link {
  display: inline-block;
  padding: 12px 16px;
  min-height: 48px;
  min-width: 48px;
}
```

## Typography

- Base font size: minimum 18px, default 22px
- Line height: minimum 1.6
- Never use light font weights (< 400) for body text
- Maximum line length: 65ch — beyond this, reading becomes tracking work
- Use a system font stack or a dyslexia-friendly font (OpenDyslexic as an option)

## Layout

- One article at a time. No infinite scroll. No pagination that requires precise clicking.
- Navigation must be operable with large, widely spaced buttons only.
- No hover-only interactions — the primary user may be on a touch device or have tremor that makes hover unreliable.
- No timed interactions or auto-advancing content.

## Contrast

- Minimum contrast ratio: 4.5:1 for body text (WCAG AA)
- Target: 7:1 for high contrast mode (WCAG AAA)
- High contrast mode must be togglable and the preference must persist (stored in user profile)

## Semantics

- Use semantic HTML. `<article>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<header>`, `<button>` — not `<div>` with click handlers.
- Every image has an `alt` attribute. Decorative images use `alt=""`.
- Form inputs have associated `<label>` elements — never placeholder-only labels.
- HTMX dynamic regions have `aria-live` attributes where content updates without a page reload.

## Text-to-speech

- Every article has a TTS trigger button, clearly labelled ("Listen")
- TTS uses the browser Web Speech API — no library, no external service
- TTS controls (play, pause, stop) are large and always visible when active
- The currently spoken sentence should be visually highlighted
- **Graceful degradation:** if the browser does not support the Web Speech API, TTS controls must be hidden entirely (feature detection via `window.speechSynthesis`). The app must remain fully usable without TTS.

## Setup wizard

The initial configuration page must follow the same accessibility rules as the rest of the app: large touch targets, high contrast, large fonts, semantic HTML, no timed interactions. The rewrite tone field (textarea) must have a visible `<label>` and sufficient size for imprecise input. Source and topic checkboxes must be large and clearly labelled.

## Graceful degradation

The app must be usable without JavaScript. HTMX enhances it; `<a>` and `<form>` elements are the fallback. Every HTMX-enhanced action must have a non-JS equivalent route.
